    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about bread and saw the term maillard reaction. can u explain what that actually is and what temp it usually happens at? i keep getting confused between that and caramelization.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a fascinating chemical process, much more complex than just a simple browning, and it's what gives bread its wonderful, complex flavor and color. It's basically a chemical reaction between amino acids (found in proteins) and reducing sugars when heat is applied. It usually kicks off around 280°F (140°C) and goes much higher, which is how you get that perfectly crusty loaf! It's different from caramelization, which is just the sugar breaking down on its own when heated.",
      "source": "target",
