    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh okay that makes sense. so if i'm trying to get a really dark crust on a sourdough loaf, what should i be looking for in terms of the dough prep or the oven temp to make sure that reaction actually happens properly? like is there anything else that helps it along?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To get that deep, dark crust, you want to encourage the Maillard reaction to go wild, which means you need high heat and the right environment. Think about a very hot, slightly humid oven, like a very hot stone hearth, which is perfect for encouraging a crusty exterior. You can also boost the reaction by slightly increasing the sugar content in your dough, though be careful not to make it too sweet, or you'll just get pure caramelization. A high oven temperature, ideally above 450°F (230°C) initially, is key to driving that browning reaction.",
      "source": "target",
