    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "cool thanks. i've also heard that the moisture in the oven helps. is there a specific science to why steam makes the crust look better or does it just affect the temp?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Steam is crucial because it essentially keeps the surface of your dough hydrated for longer, which is vital for the initial bake. If the surface dries out too quickly, the crust sets up too early, trapping steam inside and preventing the Maillard reaction from really taking hold on the exterior. By keeping the surface moist, the crust can continue to expand and develop its complex flavors before the structure fully sets. It’s a delicate balance, really, where the steam allows for a better oven spring before the heat drives the browning.",
